# SL(2, R) manifold commitment

## Commitment

The framework's spatial manifold is $\mathrm{SL}(2, \mathbb{R})$
itself: neither a quotient $\mathrm{SL}(2, \mathbb{R}) / H$ by a
non-trivial closed subgroup $H$, nor a different three-dimensional
real Lie group.

## Relation to the repository's theorems

Two results are prerequisites for the commitment, but neither forces
it alone.

- [`three_dimensions`](three_dimensions.md).  Step 3 states: *if* the
  manifold is taken to be this group, then $d = 3$.  The conditional
  is not removed in-theorem.
- [`lie_group_characterization`](lie_group_characterization.md).
  Among connected real Lie groups of dimension three, the Bianchi
  classification singles out $\mathrm{SL}(2, \mathbb{R})$ as the
  simple non-compact case whose Iwasawa $KAN$ decomposition carries
  a single compact $\mathrm{SO}(2)$ factor.

This commitment promotes the conditional of `three_dimensions` to a
definite identification, using the Bianchi characterization as the
selection rule.

## Alternatives

The following Type 3 alternatives are distinguishable and rejected
by this commitment:

| Alternative | Why not |
|-------------|---------|
| $\mathrm{SL}(2, \mathbb{R}) / \mathrm{SO}(2) \cong \mathbb{H}^2$ | loses the compact rotational factor needed at Proof A's P7 |
| $\mathrm{SO}(3)$ or $\mathrm{SU}(2)$ (Bianchi IX) | compact; incompatible with the hyperbolic Farey tiling |
| Heisenberg group (Bianchi II) | not semisimple; the mediant action does not extend transitively |
| $\mathbb{R}^3$ (Bianchi I) | abelian; no Farey structure survives |

The rejections are commitments, not derivations.  A future argument
closing the commitment (showing that one of the repository's more
primitive requirements forces the choice) would revise this entry
from a standalone Type 3 input to a theorem.

## Role

Consumed by [`proof_A_gravity`](proof_A_gravity.md) at P5 and P7.
The Type 3 supplier for the forthcoming Proof B (quantum) will be
the same commitment: the spatial manifold is shared with Proof A;
only the coupling regime ($K = 1$ vs $K < 1$) differs.

## Remarks

- The commitment is ontological.  It asserts that the points of
  spacetime *are* the points of $\mathrm{SL}(2, \mathbb{R})$, which
  is strictly more than saying that the mediant acts on
  $\mathrm{SL}(2, \mathbb{R})$ (the action is a theorem).  The
  distinction is what makes this entry Type 3 rather than a theorem.
- Running count of Type 3 inputs after this entry: one.  A separate
  Klein-quotient commitment for the gauge substrate is logically
  distinct; it will be added when the identification-sector entries
  are ported.
